column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER VEERED TO THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY TO AVOID HITTING A HERD OF ANTELOPE.  THE RIGHT FRONT TIRE WENT OVER THE EDGE OF THE ROADWAY CAUSING THE ENTIRE VEHICLE TO ENTER THE DITCH.  THE DRIVER OVER STEERED WHILE REENTERING THE ROADWAY, CAUSING THE TRUCK AND TRAILER TO ROLL 1 1/4 TIMES. DURING THE ROLLOVER BOTH THE TRUCK TANK AND THE TRAILER TANK WERE RUPTURED CAUSING THE RELEASE OF APPROX 6000 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL.  DIRT DIKES WERE ELECTED TO PREVENT THE SPREAD OF PRODUCT.  DRIVERS ARE PREPARING TO UNDERGO EXTENSIVE SAFE DRIVING CLASSES.

FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR DRIVER APPROACHED SLOWER VEHICLES AND ATTEMPTED TO PASS.  AS HE SWUNG OUT TO PASS, THE DRIVER SIDE REAR SPRINGS BROKE.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO STEER TO A SAFE STOP BUT LOST CONTROL.  THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER AND RIGHTED ITSELF.  THE METER ON THE REAR DECK SHEARED OFF.  LEAKING LP-GAS IGNITED AT RUPTURED HOSES ON REAR DECK.  THE INSUING FIRE BURNED A PRESSURE GAUGE LOCATED IN THE CENTER REAR OF TANK, CREATING ANOTHER BURNING POINT.  THE HOSES BURNED AWAY LEAVING THE METER EQUALIZING OPENING LEAKING THROUGH AN EMERGENCY SHUTOFF VALVE (ESV) THAT CLOSED LESS THAN 94% AND THE PUMP BYPASS LINE WHICH WAS CONTROLLED WITH AN ANGLE GLOBE VALVE AND BACK CHECK VALVE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENTS ARRIVED ON SCENE SHORTLY AFTER THE 911 ALARM AND BLOCKED TRAFFIC.  HOMES WITHIN 1/2 MILE WERE EVACUATED, AFFECTING APPROXIMATELY 50 FAMILIES.  ELECTRICAL POWER WAS TURNED OFF IN THE AREA BY GULF POWER COMPANY.  THE POWER COMPANY RE-ROUTED ELECTRICAL SERVICE. OKALOOSA GAS (NATURAL GAS DISTRIBUTION) ARRIVED AND CHOSE NOT TO TURN GASS OFF. FIRE DEPARTMENTS SPRAYED WATER THROUGHOUT THE NIGHTS AND DAYS OF APRIL 7 & 8 UNTIL THE MORNING OF APRIL 9.  AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 AM, THE LEAKS WERE SECURED AND THE TRUCK AND TANK WERE MOVED TO COMPANY PROPERTY VIA HEAVY DUTY WRECKER.
B/O RUPTURE DISC.  REPLACED WITH 100# DISC.
B/O RUPTURE DISC.  REPLACED 100# RUPTURE DISC.
B/0 PACKING GLAND ON BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TOP OPERATING ROD.  APPLIED SEALANT AROUND ROD.

column168: DRUMS WERE LOADED TOWARD REAR OF TRAILER - DUNNAGE WAS PUT UP AGAINST DRUMS - FREIGHT LOADED AFTER THE DRUMS WERE RAMMED INTO DUNNAGE IN ORDER TO FIT INSIDE TRAILER - CAUSING A PUNCTURED DRUM.

column42: ORGANIC PHOSPHATE MIXTURE, ORGANIC PHOSPHATE COMPOUND MIXTURE, OR ORGANIC PHOSPHORUS COMPOUND MIXTURE; SOLID OR DRY
column168: OPENED CWX TRLR 515-70112 AND BEGAN TO UNLOAD THIS SHIPMENT, WHICH WAS AT THE REAR OF TRL.  AFTER UNLOADING FIRST 2 PLTS AND RETURNING TO UNLOAD THE 3RD, A SMALL PILE OF MATERIAL WAS NOTED AT HE BASE/FLOOR OF THE 3RD PLT. UNLOADER IMMEDIATELY LOADED THE FIRST 3 PLTS BACK ON THE TRLR AND CLOSED AND LOCKED THE DOOR.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AND THEY CALLED SHIPPER WHO SENT OUT A CLEAN-UP CREW FROM THEIR LOCAL WILBUR-ELLIS OFFICE.  CLEAN-UP CREW REPAIRED BROKEN BAGS AND CLEANED UP SPILLED MATERIAL AS WELL AS DISPOSING OF THE MATERIAL IN THEIR OWN DRUM.  SHIPMENT WAS THE DELIVERED TO ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS, NAMELY WRAPPING PALLETIZED BAGS WITH CARDBOARD SHIPPER USED UNDERBAGS ON PLT AND EXTENDING IT TO AT LEAST HALF THE HEIGHT OF THE PLT WRAPPED INSIDE THE SHRINK-WRAP TO PROTECT BAGS FROM VERTICAL PORTION OF FORKS THAT NORMALLY PRESS AGAINST THEM WHILE PICKING UP THE PLTS.

WHILE INSPECTING EQUIPMENT AT TRUCKSTOP, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A DRUM OF WASTE INK HAD A SMALL CRACK IN ITS SIDE ALLOWING MATERIAL TO DRIP OUT. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THEY DISPATCHED A TEAM (VAN WATERS AND ROGERS) TO OVERPACK THE LEAKING DRUM.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL HAD DRIPPED ONTO THE GROUND.  THIS WAS DUG UP AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM. THE LOAD PROCEEDED ONTO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER CAME INTO CURVE, WENT INTO SHOULDER OF ROAD, LOAD SHIFTED, CAUSING UNIT TO OVERTURN.  IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT SPEED, DRIVER INATTENTION WAS THE CAUSE OF THIS ACCIDENT.  WE RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT WITH OUR OWN EMERGENCY RESPONSE VAN.  ALSO HIRED CONTRACTOR TO EXCAVATE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION WAS ALSO THERE TO OVER SEE THE EXCAVATION.  IT HAVE TALKED WITH OUR DRIVERS ON THIS INCIDENT, TO TRY AND PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE.  THE DRIVER THAT CAUSED THIS ACCIDENT HAS BEEN DISQUALIFIED TO DRIVER FOR ROAD & SEA TRANSPORT.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 P.M., APRIL 3, 1992, WHILE BEING INSPECTED AT THE NOTICED FIVE DRUMS THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING DURING TRANSIT.  THE FIVE DRUMS HAD DAMP AREAS AROUND THE BUNGS AND TWO OF THE FIVE DRUMS HAD DAMP AREAS FROM THE BUNGS LEADING TO THE CENTER (LOW SPOT) OF THE DRUM TOP. THERE WERE NO LIQUID PUDDLES ON THESE DRUMS NOR HAD ANY LIQUID DRIPPED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE DRUMS OR ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE HUBBARD FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE "SPILL".  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED BY ATTACHING ADSORBENT PILLOWS TO THE TOP OF THE FIVE DRUMS. THE DRIVER THEN CONTINUED TO HIS DESTINATION. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE DAMPNESS OBSERVED ON THE FIVE DRUMS WAS DUE TO OVERTIGHTENING THE BUNGS WHEREBY THE GASKETS WERE DAMAGED AND/OR NO TIGHTENING THE BUNGS ENOUGH. NOTE: THE FIVE DRUMS REFERENCED CONSISTED OF BOTH PLASTIC DRUMS AND STEEL BLADDER DRUMS.  THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUMS VARIED AS WELL.  DAMPNESS WAS OBSERVED ON CONTAINERS LABELED FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S. AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT REOCCURRENCE: GENERATOR WAS CALLED BY OUR CUSTOMER SERVICE DEPARTMENT AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT. THE GENERATOR SAID THAT ON FUTURE LOADS THEY WILL CHECK EACH DRUM TO INSURE THAT THE BUNGS ARE PROPERLY APPLIED AND TIGHTENED.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED IN LITTLE ROCK FROM HOUSTON ON 4/03/92.  WHEN TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED ODOR WAS DISCOVERED.  SUPERVISOR WAS CALLED TO INVESTIGATE.  HE FOUND ONE OF THE 3 DRUMS WITH LIQUID ACCUMULATING ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM FROM EITHER A SMALL LEAK FROM A HOLE OR THE CLOSURE WAS LOOSE. THE DRUM WAS PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND SET TO DESTINATION.

DRIVER WAS PULLING AWAY FROM TRAFFIC LIGHT WHEN HE NOTICED PRODUCT COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER HAD ONLY GONE 200 FT. FROM STOP LIGHT BEFORE HE STOPPED.  A DOME LID ON TOP OF THE TRAILER HAD BEEN LEFT IN THE OPEN POSITION AFTER LOADING.  48 GALLONS SPILLED FROM THE TRAILER ONTO THE ROADWAY.  THE EMERGENCY HAZ-MAT TEAM ALONG WITH THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT.  THE 48 GALLONS THAT WAS SPILLED WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY USING A FLOOR DRY COMPOUND.  THE FLOOR DRY COMPOUND WAS SWEPT UP AND TAKEN TO THE COMPANY TERMINAL FOR FUTURE USE.  A CITY STREET SWEEPER WAS CALLED OUT TO SCRUB AND SWEEP THE STREET.

DRIVERS TRAVELING ON 1-75, 15 TO 20 MILES NORTH OF KNOXVILLE, TENNESSEE, WHEN THEY NOTICED VAPOR COMING FROM TRAILER.  VEHICLE WAS SAFELY PULLED OFF THE ROAD.  DRIVERS FOUND VAPOR COMING OUT OF THE TRAILER CABINET DOORS. THE DRIVERS OPENED THE CABINET DOORS AND THE VAPOR DISSIPATED IMMEDIATELY.  THE VAPOR RECOVERY VALVE (V3) HAD VIBRATED OPEN 1/4 TURN AND THE DUST CAP HAD VIBRATED OFF TH VAPOR RECOVERY LINE.  DRIVERS TIGHTENED THE VALVE (V3) AND PUT THE DUST CAP BANK ON.  LEAK STOPPED IMMEDIATELY. ROAD VIBRATION CAUSED THE VALVE TO OPEN SLIGHTLY AND THE DUST CAP TO COME OFF AS THE DRIVERS CONFIRMED THAT BOTH WERE TIGHTENED AT THE  BEGINNING OF THE TRIP.  DRIVERS PROCEEDED ON TRIP WITHOUT ANY FURTHER INCIDENTS. VIBRATIONS ASSOCIATED WITH THE PIPING AND CABINET AREA OF THIS MODEL TRAILER ARE BEING REVIEWED BY COMPANY ENGINEERS IN AN EFFORT TO ELIMINATE THE PROBLEMS WITH THE DUST CAP AND THE VAPOR RECOVERY VALVE.

WHILE TRAVELING WEST ON I-12, APPROXIMATELY 12 MILES EAST OF BATON ROUGE, LOUISIANA, A PASSING MOTORIST SIGNALED TO OUR DRIVERS INDICATING A PROBLEM WITH THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVERS PULLED THE UNIT SAFELY OFF THE HIGHWAY TO INVESTIGATE.  BOTH DRIVERS WENT TO REAR OF TRAILER AND OPENED THE CABINET DOORS.  THE DRIVERS FOUND THE VAPOR RECOVERY VALVE (V3) LEAKING SLIGHTLY AND THE DUST CAP LAYING ON THE CABINET FLOOR.  ONE DRIVER CLOSED THE (V3) VALVE AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  WHEN THE DRIVER REACHED FOR THE DUST CAP, THE HYDROGEN IGNITED CAUSING A FLASH FIRE.  BOTH DRIVERS RECEIVED FIRST AND SECOND DEGREE BURNS. A COMPANY INVESTIGATION HAS DETERMINED THAT THE VAPOR RECOVERY VALVE (V3) VIBRATED OPEN.  THE ROAD CONDITIONS ON THIS STRETCH OF HIGHWAY ARE NOT PARTICULARLY GOOD AND CONTRIBUTED TO THE OPENING OF THE VALVE.  THE VALVE HAS BEEN REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER FOR ANALYSIS.  BECAUSE WE HAVE EXPERIENCED SIMILAR PRODUCT RELEASES SUCH AS THIS ON PREVIOUS OCCASSIONS AS REPORTED, WE FEEL THAT IT IS NECESSARY TO EXAMINE THE VALVE TO INSURE IT WAS FUNCTIONING CORRECTLY OR IF A DIFFERENT TYPE OF VALVE CAN BE UTILIZED TO PREVENT ACCIDENTAL OPENING FROM VIBRATIONS.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE, DRIVER NOTICED ODOR WHEN HE OPENED DOOR.  NO PROBLEMS AT PREVIOUS STOP ABOUT 1/2 MILE AWAY.  HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM FROM CONSIGNEE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED, DISCOVERED THAT VALVE HAD PARTIALLY OPENED, ALLOWING SMALL AMOUNT OF SOLUTION TO SPILL OUT ONTO FLOOR OF TRAILER.  VALVE WAS CLOSED AND CLEAN UP PROCEDURES BEGAN.  IT WAS FOUND THAT THE VALVE WAS NOT PROPERLY MOUNTED, ALLOWING VALVE HANDLE TO COME IN CONTACT WITH WALL OF TRAILER.  VIBRATION APPARENTLY CAUSED VALVE TO OPEN SLIGHTLY.  THERE WAS NO END CAP ON THE ASSEMBLY TO PREVENT ACCIDENTAL LEAK EVEN IF VALVE OPENED.  TANK IS OWNED BY CONSIGNEE.  THEIR INVESTIGATION REVEALED VALVE HAD BEEN MODIFIED TO MAKE IT EASIER TO OPEN.  ACTION HAS BEEN TAKEN TO HAVE VALVE CORRECTLY MOUNTED AND TO INSURE THAT END CAPS ARE REPLACED ON ASSEMBLY TO PREVENT ACCIDENTAL LEAKAGE. PHOTOS ATTACHED OF PROPERLY MOUNTED AND IMPROPERLY MOUNTED VALVES ON TWO TANKS OWNED BY CONSIGNEE. WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 84, THE DRIVER NOTICED A VAPOR CLOUD COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  AFTER FINDING A SAFE SPOT TO INVESTIGATE THE PROBLEM, THE DRIVER OPENED THE REAR CABINET DOORS.  FINDING THE 1/4 INCH LIQUID LINE TO THE LIQUID LEVEL GAUGE HAD BROKEN AT THE REAR END OF THE TANK.  THE DRIVER HAD NO MEANS TO CLOSE OF THE LEAK.  DUE TO THE MOIST ATMOSPHERE AND THE COLD OF THE ESCAPING LIQUID, A LARGE VAPOR CLOUD WAS FORMING VERY RAPIDLY.  THE IDAHO STATE POLICE ARRIVED QUICKLY AND CLOSED I-84 DUE TO VISIBILITY PROBLEMMS.  AIR PRODUCTS WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO BLOW DOWN THE TRAILER TO REDUCE THE INNER TANK PRESSURE, SLOWING DOWN THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ESCAPING.  A FIELD SERVICE TECH WAS WORKING IN THE ARE AND WAS IMMEDIATELY INSTRUCTED TO RESPOND TO THE UNIT.  UPON ARRIVAL THE SERVICE TECH WAS ABLE TO USE A MAKE SHIFT PLUG TO CONTAIN THE LEAK.  IN THE INTEREST OF SAFETY, AIR PRODUCTS DECIDED TO MOVE THE UNIT TO A LOCAL, REMOTE AREA AND MANUALLY VENT THE ENTIRE LOAD TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE NITROGEN MIXED BACK TO THE ATMOSPHERE CAUSING NO ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE.  THE UNIT WAS THEN RETURNED TO CENTERVILLE, UT, IN AN EMPTY SAFE.

A NEW BS&B, 100PSI FRANGIBLE DISC WAS INSTALLED AND THE CAR WAS PROPERLY SECURED FOR MOVEMENT. column168: A 55 GALLON POLYETHYLENE DRUM WAS BEING LOADED INTO A VAN TRAILER USING A DRUM CART.  AS THE DRIVER POSITIONED THE 55 POLYETHYLENE DRUM ON THE CAR, THE DRUM TIPPED BACKWARDS AND FELL OFF THE TAILGATE.  THE FORCE OF THE DRUM HITTING THE GROUND CAUSED THE TOP OF THE DRUM TO CRACK OPEN SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 55 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE GROUND.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS IMMEDIATELY INITIATED AND A CREW WAS DISPATCHED FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF ALBANY.  APPROXIMATELY 3, 20 X YARD ROLL-OFF CONTAINER OF SOIL SUSPECTED OF CONTAMINATION WERE REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND CLEAN EARTH WAS FILLED IN.  THESE CONTAINER ARE ON SITE AWAITING DISPOSAL AUTHORIZATION AT A PROPERLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A REOCURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, ALL DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT ALL DRUM CARTS TO INSURE THAT THE HOLDING MECHANISM WILL SUFFICIENTLY GRASP THE LIP OF THE DRUM INTENDED TO BE MOVED.

INSPECTION OF THE PLASTIC DRUM SHOWED A CRACK OF APPROX. 4" LONG IN THE BOTTOM EDGE OF THE DRUM.  APPEARS CRACK COULD HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY EITHER SITTING DRUM DOWN TOO HARD WHILE LOADING OR FROM BOUNCING UP AND DOWN DURING TRANSPORTATION.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT COSTAL MART STORE 289 S. GARRISON, LAKEWOOD, CO. HE HAD UNLOADED 1500 GAL. OF A 1800 GAL. ORDER, HE SWITCHED TO THE COMPARTMENT WITH THE 300 GALS. THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN FLOWING ABOUT 30 SEC, WHEN THE PRODUCT (UNLEADED GASOLINE) "VAPOR LOCKED" AND THE PRODUCT STARTED TO FLOW FROM THE FITTING ON THE UNDERGROUND TANK.  DRIVER SHUT OFF THE TANK VALVE AND TRIED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED PRODUCT ON THE STATION PROPERTY, GASOLINE GOT IN TO THE GUTTER AND SOME (ABOUT 5 TO 10 GALS) GOT INTO THE STORM SEWER.  THE DRIVER FLAGGED DOWN A LAKEWOOD POLICEMAN ASKED THAT HE CALL THE FIRE DEPT. THE FIRE DEPT, AND THE CITY OF LAKEWOOD EMERGENCY RESPONSE PEOPLE PUT ABSORBENTS DOWN TO SOAK UP THE PRODUCT. WARD TRANSPORT ALSO SENT RESPONSE PEOPLE TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. DURING OUR INVESTIGATION WE FIND THAT THE FITTING ON THE UNDERGROUND TANK WAS NOT TIGHT, DUE TO THE BUILD UP OF DIRT UNDER THE FITTING, THUS ALLOWING THE FUEL TO FLOW OUT OF THE FITTING.  THIS WAS NOT A TANK FAILURE (MC-306).

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS TRANSFERRING OIL FROM ONE TANK IN THE REFINERY TO ANOTHER TANK IN THE REFINERY.  HE WAS FOLLOWING A REFINERY EMPLOYEE IN A PICKUP.  THEY LED HIM INTO THE TANK FARM AND WHILE MAKING A RIGHT TURN, THE TRAILER WENT OFF OF THE DIKE AND OVERTURNED TAKING THE TRACTOR WITH IT.  BECAUSE THEY WERE TRANSFERRING WITHIN THE REFINERY, THE DRIVER DIDN'T LOCK DOWN THE DOME LIDS AND THIS IS WHAT CAUSED PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT.  THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED INSIDE THE DIKE AREA OF A STORAGE TANK SO THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THIS AREA.  MONTANA REFINERY CLEANED UP PRODUCT. IT WAS SNOWING WHEN THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED AND THERE WAS 1-2 INCHES OF SNOW ON THE GROUND.  VISIBILITY WAS NOT THE BEST.  THE DIKE THAT THE DRIVER WAS TURNING ONTO WAS 14 FEET WIDE.  HE SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN IN THIS AREA WITH CONDITIONS THE WAY THEY WERE.

ADVISED DOCK CREW TO BE EXTREMELY CAUTIOUS WHEN UNLOADING AWKWARD AND OVERSIZED FREIGHT NEAR STEEL DRUMS.  DAMAGED DRUM ACCEPTED IN RECOVERY DRUM BY CONSIGNEE.

DRIVER TURNED INTO I-10 TRUCK RECEIVING AREA FROM STREET MAKING A COMPLETE 360 DEGREE TURN IN ORDER TO LINE UP REAR OF TRAILER WITH LOADING DOCK. AFTER BACKING TO UNLOADING AREA, DRIVER EXITED TRACTOR AND NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM UNDER THE TRAILER IN NOSE AREA.  DRIVER PROCEEDED TYO ENTER THE VAN TO LOCATE SOURCE OF SPILL.  THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE PLASTIC CONTAINER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS PINCHED IN BETWEEN TWO PALLETS OF FREIGHT.  DRIVER PROCEEDED TO DISLODGE AND SECURE THE CONTAINER AT REAR OF TRAILER.  DRIVER TURNED CONTAINER UPSIDE DOWN TO STOP LEAKAGE.  THE DRIVER THEN CALLED DISPATCH WHO IN TURN CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND NOTIFIED TERMINAL MANAGER AND SAFETY DEPARTMENT.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS WE WILL NOT LOAD HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN BETWEEN PALLETS.

column168: WHILE LOADING A CYLINDER OF NITROGEN LIQUID THE CYLINDER TIPPED OVER IN THE FORWARD CARGO COMPARTMENT OF THE AIRCRAFT SPILLING ONTO THE CARGO FLOOR.  THE CYLINDER WAS TRANSPORTING OXEN SEMEN.  THE VENT HOLES AT THE TOP OF THE CANNISTER ALLOWED THE LIQUID TO ESCAPE.  NITROGEN LIQUID FROZE UPON CONTACT WITH THE FLOOR AND EVAPORATED AFTER ABOUT 30 MINUTES.  ANY REMAINING RESIDUE WAS WIPED UP FROM THE FLOOR.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS FLOWN TO A MAINTENANCE BASE FOR A THOROUGH INSPECTION AND WAS RELEASED WITHOUT ANY DAMAGE CAUSED BY THE SPILL.

OUR DRIVER WAS STOPPED A SHORT DISTANCE DOWN THE ROAD AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT.  HE CHECKED HIS TRAILER AND FOUND THAT THE AIR VALVE ON TOP OF HIS TRAILER WAS NOT SECURELY CLOSED. column168: KENAN TRANSPORT COMPANY DRIVER WAS MAKING DELIVERY INTO A 2500 GALLON ABOVE GROUND TANK.  AFTER STARTING PRODUCT/PUMP DRIVER CHECKED VENT ON TANK.  IT SEEMED LIKE IT WAS VENTING.  HE THEN RAISED RPM'S TO 800 AND PRODUCT BEGAN TO COME OUT OF VENT, LOSING A TOTAL OF 20 GALLONS WHICH WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY THEIR PERSONNEL AND OUR DRIVER.
THE HOSE WAS TOO SHORT SO DRIVER MOVED ABOUT 10 FEET CLOSER BUT WHEN HE DID HE FORGOT TO CLOSE THE DOME LID AND PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT.

WHEN DRIVER FINISHED MAKING HOOK UP HE OPENED VALVE AND NOTICED A LEAK AT THE END OF THE HOSE AT THE CONSIGNEE'S TANK AND SHUT OFF THE PRODUCT FLOW. HE REMOVED THE LINE AND HANDED IT OVER THE DIKE WALL TO THE RECEIVER-UNLOADER PERSONNEL.  AS THE UNLOADER STARTED TO WALK BACK TO THE TANKER HE DROPPED THE HOSE AND SOME PRODUCT SPLASHED UP AND HIT HIM ON THE FACE.  ALSO, ABOUT 1/2 GALLON RAN INTO THE PIT.  THE UNLOADER WASHED IT OFF AND SAID HE WAS ALRIGHT.

WHEN DELIVERY TANK WENT EMPTY THE AIR BLOWING INTO THE STORAGE TANK CAUSED AIR AND MIST TO COME OUT OF THE STORAGE TNAK VENTING LINE.  THE GROUND WAS WET AT THE END OF THE VENT PIPE AND THE CONSIGNEE WASHED THE AREA DOWN WITH WATER.

column168: DURING TRANSPORT OF 1,200 GALLONS OF TURBINE ENGINE FUEL FROM BERLIN, CT TO NORWALK, CT ON ROUTE 95 SOUTHBOUND, THE DRIVER WAS "WAVED OVER' BY ANOTHER DRIVER ON THE HIGHWAY, WHO EVIDENTLY NOTICED A PROBLEM WITH OUR VEHICLE. OUR DRIVER PULLED OVER AND DISCOVERED A LEAK AT THE OUTLET PIPE FROM THE FRONT COMPARTMENT OF THE CARGO TANK.  HE IMMEDIATELY RADIOED FOR ASSISTANCE AND BEGAN CONTAINING THE SPILL.  ASSISTANCE ARRIVED SOON, INCLUDING ANOTHER TANKER INTO WHICH THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED, STOPPING THE LEAK.  IN TOTAL APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS SPILLED.  IT WAS CONTAINED IN THE SURROUNDING SOIL AND SUBSEQUENTLY EXCAVATED. THE PRODUCT LEAKED THROUGH A CRACK AT A SHEAR POINT ON THE PIPING.  THE INTERNAL VALVE FAILED.  THERE IS NO EVIDENCE OF THE PIPE BEING STRUCK BY ANY ROAD OBSTACLE.  THE TANK PIPING WAS DESIGNED SUCH THAT MUCH OF THE PIPING WAS RIGIDLY FIXED TO THE FRAME, INCLUDING THE PORTION WHERE THE LEAK OCCURRED.  THERE ARE FEW FLEXIBLE COUPLINGS TO ABSORBED SHOCK VIBRATION. METAL FATIGUE OVER TIME LIKELY RESULTED IN THE CRACK.  THE TANK IS BEING MODIFIED TO INCORPORATE FLEXIBLE COUPLINGS.  THE VALVE IS BEING REPLACED. THE CARGO TANK IS BEING REPAIRED AND REQUALIFIED BY A LICENSED FACILITY.

PRODUCT WAS BEING OFFLOADED FROM CARGO TANK INTO CUSTOMER'S DRUMS THROUGH USE OF TRACTOR MOUNTED TRANSFER PUMP, TRANFER HOSES, AND A DRUMMING NOZZLE.  PLANT EMPLOYEE WAS OPERATING THE DRUMMING NOZZLE AND DRIVER WAS OPERATING THE TRANSFER PUMP.  DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, THE PLANT EMPLOYEE SENSED AN UNUSUAL PRESSURE BUILD UP IN THE TRANFER HOSES AND OPENED THE DRUMMING NOZZLE.  THIS RESULTED IN APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED INSIDE THE PLANT FACILITY BEFORE DRIVER COULD GET THE PUMP SHUT DOWN. PRESSURE BUILT UP WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY A DEFECTIVE RELIEF VALVE ON THE TRANSFER PUMP. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY PLANT PERSONNEL.

DRIVER DISCOVERED A SMALL LEAK THAT APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM SOMEWHERE AROUND THE LANDING GEAR WHILE ACCOMPLISHING A TIRE CHECK EN ROUTE TO DESTINATION.  BECAUSE LEAK WAS SO SMALL THAT IT WAS BASICALLY EVAPORATING BEFORE IT REACHED THE GROUND, IT WAS DECIDED TO TAKE THE CARGO TANK TO A COMPANY FACILITY THAT WAS LEEN THAN 30 MINUTES. ONCE AT THE FACILITY THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK WITHOUT INCIDENT.  AN ESTIMATED ONE PINT OR LESS WAS LOST DURING THE ENTIRE ORDEAL. LEAK WAS DISCOVERED TO BE COMING FROM A THIN CRACK IN A WELD WHERE AND INTRANSIT HEAT LINE ENTERED THE FRONT OF THE TANK.  CAP TANK HAS BEEN TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL REPAIRS.

CARGO TANK DEVELOPED A LEAK WHILE BEING UNLOADED.  APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN A CATCH BASIN AT THE CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADING FACILITY.  PRODUCT DRAINED INTO A HOLDING TANK AND WAS SUBSEQUENTLY PUMPED INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S PRODUCT STORAGE TANK.  LEAK WAS APPARENTLY CAUSED BY FAILURE OF A WELD SEAM ALONG WITH FAILURE OF THE TANK LINER.  CARGO TANK WAS LEASED FROM ROLLINS BY OCCIDENTAL CORPORATION. ALL ACTIONS NECESSARY TO HANDLE THE SPILL WERE HANDLED BY OCCIDENTAL PERSONNEL.  OCCIDENTAL PERSONNEL ALSO HANDLING REPAIRS TO THE CARGO TANK WITH ROLLINS.

column168: CARGO TANK WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING UPON ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE BY THE DRIVER.  LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE AREA AROUND THE INTERNAL/EXTERNAL VALVE. LEAK WAS CONTAINED IN A BUCKET (APPROXIMATELY 2 TEASPOONS EVERY 30 MINUTES).  PRODUCT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY UNLOADED INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK. TRAILER WAS THEN TAKEN TO OUR LOUISVILLE TERMIANL WHERE IT WAS CLEANED AND INSPECTED.  THE LEAK WAS FOUND TO BE A COMBINATION OF TWO THINGS.  THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS NOT FULLY SEATED AND WAS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO FLOW INTO CAVITY BETWEEN THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES.  IT WAS ALSO FOUND THAT THE V-CLAMP HOLDING THE EXTERNAL VALVE IN ITS HOUSING HAD NOT BEEN SECURELY TIGHTENED WHEN LAST INSTALLED.  REPAIRS/CORRECTIONS HAVE BEEN MADE. SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT CONTAINED IN BUCKET WAS DISPOSED OF BY PLANT PERSONNEL.

column168: EAGLE TRANSPORT WAS CONTRACTED BY CLEVELAND INDUSTRIES TO HELP WITH A LINE FLUSH PROJECT AT DOUGLAS INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT IN CHARLOTTE, NC.  WE WOULD PROVIDE FOR EQUIPMENT AND MANPOWER. BEFORE THE JOB BEGAN WE DISCUSSED THE JOB WITH CLEVELAND INDUSTRIES, WE SHOWED OUR HOSES AND EXPLAINED TO THEM THAT THESE WERE NON-PRESSURE, GRAVITY DROP HOSES, THEN OUT TERMINAL MANAGER ASKED HOW MUCH PRSSURE AND BACK PRESSURE WOULD BE USED AND THEY TOLD HIM THAT THE PRESSURES BEING USED WOULD NOT EXCEED 10 PSI.  WE STARTED THE JOB AND OUR HOSES AND THE HOSES COULD NOT TAKE THE PRESSURE, RESULTING IN A SPILL.  WE CHECKED THE PSI AND AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL THE PRESSURE WAS 65 OR 75 LBS. THIS SPILL IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION, WE BELIEVE THAT THE SPILL COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF CLEVELAND INDUSTRIES HAD NOT USED OUR EQUIPMENT IMPROPERLY.  TOO MUCH PRESSURE.  THE AIRPORT CONTROLLED THE PUMPS.  THE SITE WAS CLEANED AND WORK RESUMED WITH STEEL PIPE BEING USED INSTEAD OF OUR HOSES.  THIS IS CLASSIFIED AS A NON-PREVENTABLE SPILL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT WAS CREATED WHEN OUR SINGLE AXLE DELIVERY TRUCK DISPLAYING 1993 COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID PLACARDS HIT A CONCRETE LANE DIVIDER AND OVERTURNED ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE ON MISSOURI HWY 79 NEAR O'FALLON, MO.  THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INVOLVED WAS N-SERVE 24 NITROGEN STABILIZER, A FERTILIZER ADDITIVE, WHICH IS CLASSIFIED AS A COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID.  OUR TRUCK CONTAINED A 300 GALLON CAPACITY STAINLESS STEEL MINI-BULK TANK WITH 140 GALLONS OF N-SERVE 24 NITROGEN STABILIZER INSIDE. WHEN THE TRUCK OVERTURNED THE MINI-BULK TANK ALSO TURNED OVER AND BEGAN LEAKING N-SERVE 24 NITROGEN STABILIZER OUT OF THE FILL HOLE COVER GASKET. APPROIMATELY 116 GALLONS OF N-SERVE 24 LEAKED ONTO 2 PALLETS OF CALCIUM NITRATE FERTILIZER (80 X 50 LB. BAGS = 4,000 LBS.) AND WAS MOSTLY ABSORBED INTO THE BAGGED CALCIUM NITRATE WITHIN THE BOX OF OUR TRUCK.  OUR NEW LONDON, MO LOCATION MANAGER AND 2 EMPLOYEES ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 PM TO CLEANUP THE MATERIAL UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE ST. CHARLES COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM.  THE HAZMAT TEAM HAD BEEN SUMMONED BY THE O'FALLON POLICE DEPARTMENT WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE TRUCK WAS DISPLAYING 1993 PLACARDS. OUR EMPLOYEES REMOVED ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL FROM THE TRUCK BOX AND PUT IT IN PLASTIC RECOVERY BAGS.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF N-SERVE 24 NITROGEN STABILIZER WAS FOUND IN AN INDENTATION OF THE RAODSIDE DITCH WHEN THE TRUCK WAS UPRIGHTED.  THE N-SERVE 24 AND THE CONTAMINATED SOIL FROM THIS INDENTATION WAS CLEANED UP AND PUT IN 3 PLASTIC RECOVERY BAGS.  ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY 11:30 PM AND THIS MATERIAL WAS HAULED TO OUR NEW LONDON, MO WAREHOUSE.  THE MATERIAL WILL BE STORED THERE UNTIL ARRANGEMENTS CAN BE MADE FOR RPOPER DISPOSAL. THERE WAS NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGING FAILURE IN THIS INCIDENT.  THE SPILLAGE WAS THE DIRECT RESULT OF THE VEHICLE ACCIDENT OVERTURNING THE MINI-BULK TANK CONTAINING THE N-SERVE 24 NITROGEN STABILIZER.  THE FILL HOLE COVER (MANWAY) IS DESIGNED TO RELEASE PRESSURE BUILDUP.  THE MANWAY OF THE OVERTURNED MINI-BULK TANK PERFORMED AS DESIGNED. THIS WRITTEN REPORT IS THE FOLLOWUP TO OUR PHONE REPORT TO THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, PHONE NUMBER 1-800-424-8802, REPORT NO. 118274. CERTIFIED MAIL NO P 911 927 927.

DURING UNLOADING OF FUEL OIL FROM A TANKER TRUCK (7000 GALLON CAPACITY) TO A 49,000 GALLON EMERGENCY DIESEL GENERATOR FUEL OIL STORAGE TANK, AN OVERFILL OCCURRED ON APRIL 23, 1992 AT 1734.  THE LEVEL GAUGE FOR THE RECEIVING TANK INDICATED SUFFICIENT CAPACITY (BY A CONSIDERABLE MARGIN) AVAILABLE IN THE TANK TO HOLD THE REMAINING 400 GALLONS IN THE 7000 GALLON TANK TRUCK.  HOWEVER, THE OIL OVERFLOWED THROUGH THE STORAGE TANK CROOK NECK OVERFLOW LINE.  THE OIL FLOW WAS QUICKLY STOPPED BY THE DRIVER OF THE TANK TRUCK, BUT AN ESTIMATED 50 GALLONS OF OIL HAD OVERFLOWED TO A CONCRETE PAD AND GROUND NEARBY.  THE EQUIPMENT OPERATOR PRESENT INITIATED THE CONTAINMENT OF THE SPILL SO THAT NO OIL REACHED STORM DRAINS IN THE AREA.  THE CONTAMINATED DIRT WAS REMOVED AND IS AWAITING DISPOSAL DETERMINATION/APPROVAL.  OTHER IMMEDIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS INCLUDED STATIONING A 55 GALLON DRUM UNDER THE OVERFLOW, INITIATION OF A FUNTIONAL CHECK, AND LONG TERM RESOLUTION FOR THE LEVEL INSTRUMENTATION PROBLEM ENCOUNTERED.  A CHANGE WAS ALSO INITIATED TO THE RECEIVING PROCEDURE TO ADD A WARNING NOTE CONCERNING THE GAUGE.

column168: THIS INCIDENT DOES NOT INVOLVE A PACKAGE FAILURE.  ONE OF THE BARRELS HAD SOME CONTAMINATED DIRT ON THE UNDERSIDE FROM WHERE IT HAD BEEN STORED AT THE MINE.  DURING TRANSPORT, THIS DROPPED FROM THE UNDERSIDE OF THE DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  AS THE BARRELS WERE UNLOADED AND INSPECTED, ALL WERE FOUND TO BE INTACT AND THERE WAS NO INDICATION OF A PROBLEM.  THIS BARREL WAS POSITIONED ON THE TRAILER IN THE NOSE, DRIVER'S SIDE CORNER.  BECAUSE OF THE DIRT'S LOW ACTIVITY LEVEL AND IT'S LOCATION IN THE CORNER, IT WAS ACCIDENTALLY MISSED DURING THE OUTBOUND SURVEY.  THE TRAILER WAS BROUGHT TO JOPLIN WHERE THESE TRAILERS ARE KEPT BETWEEN SHIPMENT AND THE CONTAMINATION WAS FOUND PRIOR TO SOME MINOR REPAIR WORK. THE DIRT WAS CLEANED UP OFF THE FLOOR AND PACKAGE AS LIMITED QUANTITY AND RETURNED TO ALLIED SIGNAL ALONG WITH THE TRAILER FOR PROPER DETERMINATION.
IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TOP CLOSURE CAME OFF DURING TRANSIT.  THE CLOSURE WAS SECURELY FASTENED.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED ABOUT THE CLOSURE NOT PERFORMING CORRECTLY FOR FUTURE CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1135 HOURS, MONDAY, APRIL 20, 1992, DOT/FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR R. BUNDY REPORTED TO CONRAIL PERSONNEL AT THE CONRAIL PAULSBORO, NJ RAIL YARD THAT HE HAD FOUND A RESIDUE TANK CAR OF LIQUIFIED GAS (NDYX-30009) LEAKING PRODUCT WHILE INSPECTING RAIL CARS IN TRAIN WPCA-11.  TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED TO THE MOBILE OIL COKE YARD AND CHEMTREC SHIPPER AND LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS NOTIFIED. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM MOBIL OIL CORPORATION ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 1210 HOURS, APRIL 20, 1992, AND UPON INSPECTION FOUND THAT THE "B" END LIQUID LINE VALVE AND PLUG WERE LOOSE ALLOWING RESIDUAL PRODUCT VAPOR TO ESCAPE FROM THE EMPTY TANK CAR. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY THE MOBIL PERSONNEL TO SECURE THE LEAK AND CAR WAS INSPECTED BY RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM HUNTSMAN POLYPROPYLENE PRIOR TO CLEARING THE CAR TO DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 HOURS. TANK CAR HAD BEEN PULLED FROM THE HUNTSMAN FACILITY AT 0100 HOURS, APRIL 20, 1992 AND MOVED TO THE CONRAIL YARD IN PAULSBORO.  NO LEAK OF PRODUCT WAS DETECTED AT THE TIME THE CAR WAS ACCEPTED INTO TRANSPORTATION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 2115 HOURS, SATURDAY, APRIL 19, 1992, EMPLOYEES OF THE CONRAIL BAYVIEW RAIL YARD IN BALTIMORE, MD OBSERVED LIQUID PRODUCT NEAR THE TOP VALVE ASSEMBLY OF TANK CAR GATX-41054 (PHOSPHORIC ACID) AFTER TANK CAR HAD BEEN SWITCHED INTO A STANDING CAR ON TRACK 48 OF THE CLASSIFICATION YARD.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED. AT 0910 HOURS, APRIL 20, 1992, PERSONNEL FROM LEBANON CHEMICAL (CONSIGNEE) RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AND UPON INSPECTION, FOUND A RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK IN THE CAR'S SAFETY VENT.  THE RUPTURED DISK WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A COMPATIBLE 100 POUND RATED FRANGIBLE DISK. CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 0930 HOURS, APRIL 20, 1992.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1430 HOURS, MONDAY, APRIL 20, 1992, EMPLOYEES WORKING AT THE CONRAIL PAVONIA RAIL YARD IN CAMDEN, NJ REPORTED ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR EDCX-1615 (NITRIC ACID, FUMING).  CAR HAD JUST BEEN SWITCHED TO TRACK 1 IN THE CLASSIFICATION YARD WHEN ODOR WAS NOTICED.  TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC, SHIPPER, CONSIGNEE, AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED. AT 1830 HOURS, TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED BY AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR A.L. RICHTER AND H.R. ELLIOTT, SUPERVISOR-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SECTION FOR CONRAIL.  INSPECTION REVEALED A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF LIQUID PRODUCT ON THE FITTINGS AND PRESSURE PLATE WITHIN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING; HOWEVER, NO LEAK COULD BE DETECTED.  INDICATION IS THAT 45 PSI SAFETY VALVE HAD OPERATED ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID TO BE RELEASED AND ALSO CAUSING THE ODOR SMELLED BY THE EMPLOYEES.  VALVE HAD APPARENTLY PROPERLY RESEATED AFTER ACTIVATION. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM DUPONT (CONSIGNEE) ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE CAR AT 2000 HOURS AND REINSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND SAFETY VALVE.  VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE FOUND SECURE AND CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 2055 HOURS, APRIL 20, 1992.

STOPPED TO CHECK LOAD.  NOTICED A ODOR.  SAW A LITTLE DRIP IN ONE OF THE COUPLINGS.  WIPED UP DRIPS AND BROUGHT IN AND TIGHTENED COUPLING.

PHYSICAL EVIDENCE-1) LOCKED WHEEL SKIDMARKS, 2) VEHICLE DEBRIS AND 3) GAS/OIL (REFER TO LEGEND FOR LOCATIONS). STATEMENTS-P-1 (MARTINEZ) STATED WAS OBTAINED BY OFFICER LESSENTINE #10. P-1 RELATED HIS STATEMENT IN SPANISH TO A. GARCIA #217 OF ADAMS AMBULANCE #40.  P-1 RELATRED IN ESSENCE THAT HE WAS TRAVELLING S/B I-710 IN THE #2 LANE AT 55 MPH 30' BEHIND A BLK P/U.  HE RELATED THAT THE BLK P/U SLAMMED ON ITS BRAKES AND SLOWED SUDDENLY.  HE SLAMMED ON HIS BRAKES AND REAR ENDED THE P/U WHICH CAUSED HIM TO LOSE CONTROL OF V-1.  P-1 DOES NOT REMEMBER WHAT HAPPENED AFTER THAT. P-2 (SANDOVAL) RELATED HIS STATEMENT IN SPANISH TO OFFICER PEREZ #11478. P-1 RELATED IN ESSENCE THAT HE WAS TRAVELLING S/B I-710 IN THE #2 LANE AT 50 MPH.  WHEN A SMALL TAN CAR SUDDENLY APPLIED ITS BRAKES IN FRONT OF HIM TO CHANGE INTO THE #3 LANE.  HE APPLIED HIS BRAKES AND WAS REAR ENDED BY A BOBTAIL.  HE DIDN'T SEE ANY OF THE ACCIDENT BECAUSE HE WAS TRYING TO REGAIN CONTROL OF V-2. P-3 (NEZ) RELATED IN ESSENCE THAT HE WAS TRAVELLING S/B I-710 IN THE #3 LANE AT 50 MPH.  HE OBSERVED A VEHICLE CHANGE FROM THE #2 LANE TO THE OFF-RAMP CUTTING IN FRONT OF THE BOBTAIL WHICH WAS S/B IN THE #2 LANE AHEAD OF V-3.  P-3 RELATED THAT THE BOBTAIL SLAMMED ON ITS BRAKES AND HE SAW SMOKE EVERYWHERE.  HE OBSERVED THE BOBTAIL SLIDING SIDEWAYS INTO THE #3 LANE.  P-3 THEN BRAKED HARD AND SWERVED TO THE RIGHT TO AVOID COLLIDING WITH THE BOBTAIL.  HE FELT A JOLT AND CAME TO A STOP.  HE IMMEDIATELY EXITED HIS VEHICLE TO SEE IF EVERYONE WAS OK. P-4 (MCALLISTER) RELATED IN ESSENCE THAT SHE WAS TRAVELLING S/B I-710 IN THE #4 LANE AT 55 MPH.  SHE OBSERVED A BOBTAIL IN THE #2 LANE 100' IN FRONT OF HER.  SHE RELATED THAT THE BOBTAIL LOCKED ITS WHEELS AND STARTED SLIDING SIDEWAYS.  SHE BRAKED HARD FEARING THE BOBTAIL WAS GOING TO SLIDE INTO HER VEHICLE.  SHE DOES NOT REMEMBER WHAT HAPPENED AFTER THAT. OPINIONS AND CONCLUSIONS-V-2 (CHEV. P/U) WAS TRAVELLING S/B I-710 IN THE #2 LANE AT 50 TO 55 MPH.  V-1 (FORD BOBTAIL) WAS TRAVELLING S/B I-710 IN THE #2 LANE AT 50 TO 55 MPH 30' BEHIND V-2.  V-3 (KENWORTH TANKER) WAS TRAVELLING S/B I-710 IN THE #3 LANE AT 50 TO 55 MPH TO THE REAR OF V-2. V-4(CHEV BLAZER) WAS TRAVELLING S/B I-710 IN THE #4 LANE AT 50 TO 55 MPH TO THE REAR OF V-3.  THIS COLLISION OCCURRED WHEN V-3 SLOWED SUDDENLY DUE TO A VEHICLE IN FRONT OF IT SLOWING.  P-1 APPLIED HIS BRAKES ABRUPTLY LOCKING V-1'S WHEELS.  P-1 LOST CONTROL OF V-1 AND REAR ENDED V-2.  P-3 OBSERVED V-1 SLIDING OUT OF CONTROL INTO HIS LANE.  P-3 BRAKED HARD AND SWERVED TO THE RIGHT IN AN ATTEMPT TO AVOID CONTACT WITH V-1.  V-3'S L/SIDE SIDESWIPED THE R/SIDE OF V-1.  V-3'S TRAILER THEN JACK-KNIFED CAUSING IT TO ROLL ONTO ITS L/SIDE STRIKING THE R/REAR CORNER OF V-1.  THE FORCE OF THE IMPACT THEN CAUSED THE TRAILER TO UPRIGHT AND THEN CONTINUE TO ROLL ONTO ITS R/SIDE ROLLING COMPLETELY OVER THE TOP OF V-4 WHICH WAS IN THE #4 LANE. POINTS OF IMPACT-PO1 #1 (V-1 VS V-2) 356' N OF THE N/RDWY EDGE OF IMPERIAL HWY AND 30' E/OF THE W/RD

AT 1000 HRS ON 04/29/92 I WENT TO THE DANGEROUS GOODS HOLD AREA ON OUR DOCK, TO LOOK FOR A PIECE OF FREIGHT.  I NOTICED A "CHEMICAL SMELL" AND TRIED TO IDENTITY ITS SOURCE.  THE SMELL CAME FROM A SMALL FIBERBOARD BOC OF TWO DIFFERENT FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS ALL PACKED IN ONE.  THERE WAS NO VISIBLE INDICATION OF A LEAK (I.E. WET FIBERBOARD), ONLY A STRONG SMELL FROM THE BOX.  WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER OF THE PROBLEM, SHORTLY THEREAFTER THEY CAME TO RETRIEVE THE FREIGHT FROM OUR DOCK.  WE DID NOT OPEN THE BOX, IT IS UNKNOWN WHAT CAUSED THE ODOR TO COME FROM THE BOX, ONE OR BOTH OF THE INNER PACKAGINGS MAY HAVE BEEN DAMAGED EN ROUTE TO OUR WAREHOUSE. NOTHING OUT OF THE ORDINARY WAS REPORTED BY THE DRIVER.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT DM STATION TO EFFECT DELIVERY OF GASOLINE INTO THEIR UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS.  THE LOCATION IS EQUIPPED WITH "REMOTE DROP FILLS" - IN OTHER WORDS WE HOOK-UP TO AND DROP THE GASOLINE INTO A FILL PIPE THAT IS REMOTE TO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK (A PIPE RUNS UNDERGROUND FROM THE STORAGE TANK TO THE REMOTE FILL).  THE TANKS WERE GAUGED PRIOR TO OUR OFFLOADING BY OUR DRIVER AND BY STORE MANAGER; THE STICK READINGS REFLECTED THAT THE PRODUCT WOULD FIT INTO TANK AND OFFLOADING WAS INITIATED.  JUST AS OUR TANKER VESSEL WAS DRAINING DRY (FROM THE UNLOADING PROCESSS) GASOLINE CAME OUT OF THE DIRECT FILL CAP OUT OF THE STORAGE TANK-WHICH IS LOCATED ACROSS THE CUSTOMERS LOT FROM THE OFFLOADING AREA. THE CAP IS SUPPOSSED TO BE SEALED AND CLOSED AT ALL TIMES-CLEVELAND FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED ALONG WITH HAZMAT TEAM.  STATION WAS CITED FOR IMPROPER OFFLOADING SYSTEM AND DEFECTIVE FILL CAP.  THE SPILL SITUATION WAS FAULT OF DIARY MART.  DIARY MART WAS INSTRUCTED TO HAVE A NEW UP TO CODE INSTATLLAION ON PLACE AND HAVE ALREADY INACTED CONSTRUCTION TO DOSO.  OHIO EPA WAS CALLED (REPORT# 4-18-1388) DIARY MART HAD SAMSEL SERVICES RESPOND AND EFFECT CLEAN-UP OF THE PRODUCT AND DISPOSAL OF SAME. WE WERE EXONERATED OF ANY LIABILITY.

column168: EMPLOYEE RON GRECO PUNCTURED DRUM WITH A FORKLIFT BLADE.  HE BEGAN GETTING ILL AND WAS PULLED FROM THE AREA BY EMPLOYEES. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, IN CONJUNCTION WITH CONTAINERIZED CHEMICAL, CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP SPILL.  WASTE WAS LEFT ON SITE IN TRAILER 11-2537 WHICH INCLUDES THE 2 DAMAGED DRUM AND ALL ABSORBENT WASTE MATERIAL.  TRAILER 15-0348, THE UNDERCARRIAGE WAS SPRAYED WITH NEUTRALIZER.  INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY EMPLOYEE NEGLIGENCE IN CARRYING OUT HIS DUTIES.  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED, OSHA WAS ON THE SCENE, CONTAINERIZED CHEMICAL REMAINS IN CHARGE OF ALL SITE CLEAN-UP.

TISDALE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED CHEMTREC.  A DRY SAFETY ABSORBENT WAS ADDED AND THE SPILL WAS THROUGHLY DILUTED WITH WATER.  REMAINING CONTENTS AND CONTAINER WAS DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE.

column168: CAR INSPECTOR, BLEEDING OFF TRACK 137, REPORTED AN ODOR AROUND THE EAST END AT APPROXIMATELY 1420 HOURS.  WHEN I ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 1440 HOURS, I FOUND NATX 76835 DRIPPING FROM BOTH SIDES OF PLATE THAT HAS REPLACED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE LEAK WAS APPROXIMATELY TWO DROPS EVERY MINUTE.  I LOCATED AN ALLEN WRENCH AND TIGHTENED EIGHT ALLEN BOLTS HOLDING PLATE TO CAR.  I THEN HAD THE GENERAL OFFICE CONTACT MR. CLIFF SHUPE OF THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD COMPANY.  UPON MR. SHUPE'S ARRIVAL THE LEAK HAD STOPPED DRIPPING.  MR. SHUPE CONTACTED CHEM TREC AND CHEM TREC HAD ROHM HAAS CONTACT MR. SHUPE.  AT THAT TIME, A PATCH OF METAL TAPE AND EPOXY WITH LEAD WOOD PACKING AROUND THE EDGE OF THE PLATE WAS DISCUSSED.  THIS WAS DONE AND THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO TRAVEL TO IT'S DESTINATION.

AT APPROX 1050 4/26/92 ROB SANDERS NOTIFIED ME THAT PAUL MARRON HAD SPIKED A DRUM OF CORROSIVE.  I HAD ROB AND PAUL GET FLOOR DRY AND SODA ASH TO CONTAIN SPILL IN TRAILER.  WE SPREAD SODA ASH UNDER TRAILER, THEN MOVED IT TO THE NORTH SIDE OF THE YARD.  I NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND WAITED FOR THE CALL BACK FROM THE SHIPPER. AT APPROX 1120 THE FIRE DEPT ARRIVED AND TOOK CHARGE OF THE AREA AFFECTED.  ELEVEN PEOPLE WENT TO DEPAUL HOSP FOR OBSERVATION AND CHECK UP.  ALL WERE RELEASED TO RETURN TO WORK.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE FIRE DEPT.  AFTER CLEAN UP, WE HAD ONE RECOVERY DRUM WITH EMPTY BARRELL IN IT AND ONE DRUM OF SODA AND FLOOR DRY WITH RESIDUE FROM SPILL.  TRAILER 17-3341 WAS SENT TO SHOP TO BE STEAMED PER HAZMAT INSPECTOR.

GREG HIGHER OF HIGH PLAINS CONTACTED MANAGER STINE AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR TRANSPORT TRUCK TO OFF-LOAD EXCESS PRODUCT. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) C. L. SHUPE WAS NOTIFIED BY L. ROSSEN, MANAGER MAINTENANCE, THAT BULKTAINER ICLU 946228 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT. column168: CHARLIE GEORGIA WAS MAKING A BLEACH DELIVERY TO SUPREME CHEMICAL WHEN TANKER WENT EMPTY.  MR. GEORGIA ALLOWED AIR TO FLOW THROUGH HOSE TO CLEAR REMAINING PRODUCT IN LINE, THE AIR CAUSED THE LINE TO JUMP AND THE CAM-LOCK FITTING SNAPPED OFF FROM THE CONNECTION TO TANK.  MR. CHARLIE GEORGIA IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF VALVE FROM TANKER.  MR. WARREN WALD OF B&B POOL WORKS WAS AT SUPREME CHEMICAL PICKING UP CHEMICALS AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT.  WHEN THE CAM-LOCK FITTING BROKE THE HOSE SWUNG AROUND AND STRUCK MR. WALDS PICK UP TRUCK IN THE DOOR, MINIMAL DAMAGE, SMALL DENT. ALSO A SMALL AMOUNT OF BLEACH SPLASHED ON DOOR.  MR. GEORGIA WASHED BLEACH OFF IMMEDIATELY.

STINE WERE ENROUTE TO PUEBLO, CO.  BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR, BOB EWOLDT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE 100 PSI BS&B FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED.  DISC WAS REPLACED WITH LIKE KIND AND SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS APPLIED TO NEUTRALIZE SPILLED ACID.  CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED AS FOLLOWS: JIM LAFRENZ WAS PULLING AN ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANK FROM OUR CALAMUS PLANT TO MR. LYLE GOETTSCH'S BURMEISTER FARM.  THE UNIT CONSISTED OF A GMC 3/4 TON PICK-UP PULLING A 1450 NURSE TANK ON A STANDARD RUNNING GEAR. THE DRIVER PROCEEDED FROM THE PLANT TO THE FARM USING THE COUNTRY ROAD SYSTEM WHICH ARE GRAVEL ROADWAYS.  IN SPRING OF THE YEAR THESE ROADS TEND TO HAVE SOFT SPOTS AND LOOSE GRAVEL AREAS DUE TO THE WINTER FREEZING AND THAWING CYCLES. MR. LAFRENZ CRESTED A SMALL HILL AND MY THEORY IS THAT THE PICK-UP GAINED A LITTLE SPEED AND THEN HIT A PATCH OF LOOSE GRAVEL.  THE TRAILER STARTED TO FISHTAIL WHICH CAUSED THE LIQUID TO MOVE IN A SIDEWAYS DIRECTION THUS ENHANCING THE FISHTAIL OF THE TRAILER THUS CAUSING EXCESSIVE SIDEWAYS MOVEMENT OF THE LIQUID CAUSING THE TANK TO TURN OVER. MR. LAFRENZ STATED HIS SPEED WAS 20-25 MPH AND IT WAS ALL HE COULD DO TO KEEP THE PICK-UP STRAIGHT.  HE LET THE DRAGGING ACTION OF THE OVERTURNED TANK STOP THE UNIT AND THE SHORT DISTANCE OF THE TRACKS CONFIRMS HIS SPEED STATEMENT. WHEN MR. LAFRENZ DETERMINED IT WAS SAFE FOR HIMSELF TO REMAIN ON THE SITE HE RADIOED FOR ASSISTANCE.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED ALONG WITH THE COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT AND MYSELF.  THE SITE OF THE ACCIDENT WAS SECURED AND PRODUCT ESCAPING FROM THE DAMAGED VALVE WAS CONTROLLED.  USING OUR OWN EQUIPMENT THE TANK WAS SET UPRIGHT AND THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER NURSE TANK.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T. R. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED BY JIM OSBURN, MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, THAT TANK CAR NATX 26818 WAS FOUND LEAKING AT THE AVONDALE YARD.  MANAGER OSBURN INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT TWO OF THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE IMPROPERLY INSTALLED AND WAS PREVENTING THE MANWAY FROM FORMING A SEAL.  MANAGER OSBURN REPOSITIONED THE BOLTS AND PROPERLY SECURED THE MANWAY COVER.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) F. H. LERCH WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANK CAR UTLX 201058 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR.  SA/HM LERCH RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 60 DROPS A MINUTE.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN A BUCKET AND PROTECTIVE SEAL EXXON 615078 WAS REMOVED FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE CLOSED TYPE GAUGING DEVICE, PLUG TO THE AIR VALVE AND ALSO THE PLUG TO THE LIQUID VALVE.  SA/HM LERCH TIGHTENED PROTECTIVE HOUSING ON THE GAUGING DEVICE, AIR VALVE PLUG, AND THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS SECURED WITH SEAL UPC 73921 AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. JIM LONG OF CHEMTREC, MARC LOUTHAN OF THE NEBRASKA STATE PATROL, FRED HOLZAPFEL OF EXXON CHEMICAL, AND JIM BOROVICH OF NEBRASKA STATE ENVIRONMENT WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

WHILE CONDUCTING ROUTINE INSPECTIONS, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D. A. DISCOVERED TANK CAR PSPX 139, LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE CAR.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PACKING WITHIN STUFFING BOX PACKING GLAND WAS TO THE STUFFING BOX VALVE. JEFF BOTTWICK OF CHEMTREC, AND JEFF ANGLE, PHILLIPS 66 COMPANY WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

MANAGER, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R. M. STINE, WAS NOTIFIED THAT CREWS REPORTED SLIGHT LEAKAGE AT NOSE OF TRAILER CSXZ 239328 WHEN IT WAS DE-RAMPED.  CHEMTREC HAD BEEN NOTIFIED AND SHIPPER HAD CALLED ADVISING THAT A LOCAL FIRM WOULD BE CONTRACTED TO HANDLE ANY CLEANUP. MR. BRUCE CRABTREE, ALONG WITH C.C. ENVIROKLEAN PERSONNEL, INSPECTED TRAILER WHICH DETERMINED SEVERAL AREAS WITHIN THE TRAILER WHERE LIQUID CONTAINED IN THE DRUM HAD SEEPED FROM AROUND THE DRUMS LIDS DUE TO SHIFTING DURING TRANSPORT.  LIQUID WAS NOT LEAKING AT THE TIME OF INSPECTION. ALL 80 DRUM WERE OFF LOADED AND INSPECTED OF WHICH 11 WERE NOTED TO HAVE LEAKED PRODUCT.  TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED AND LINED WITH PLASTIC AND ABSORBENT MATTING.  DRUM LID GASKETS WERE REPLACED ON EACH OF THE 11 LEAKERS AND TRAILER WAS RELOADED AND SECURED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.

ON 4-10-92, AT APPROXIMATELY 0046 HOURS, I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZMAT COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN UNLOAD A OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  DAVE HARP/SORT SUPERVISOR BROUGHT THIS TO MY ATTENTION.  DURING MY INVESTIGATION, I FOUND ONE FIBREBOARD BOX.  THIS FIBREBOARD BOARD BOX HAD A BLISTER PACK CONTAINING THE AIR WAYBILL AND INVOICE AFFIXED TO ITS TOP. SIDE ONE HAD "FOR RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT PURPOSES" MARKED ON IT WITH A MARKER.  SIDE TWO STATED "FRAGILE, GLASSWARE", USE BOTH HANDS", AND A DFDS TRANSPORT LABEL.  SIDE 3 HAD "THIS END UP" MARKED ON IT WITH ARROWS SHOWING THE PROPER ORIENTATION FOR THIS SHIPMENT. INSIDE THIS FIBREBOARD FOX, I FOUND 3 BROWN, GLASS BOTTLES WITH PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES.  TWO OF THE THREE WERE HALF FULL (CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF PRODUCT EACH), WITH NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE.  THE THIRD BOTTLE WAS ONLY ON E QUARTER FULL AND THE CLOSURE WAS LOOSE.  I DEDUCTED THAT THIS WAS THE ONLY BOTTLE THAT SPILLED.  THE PRODUCT INSIDE THE GLASS BOTTLES HAS A STRONG HYDROCARBON ODOR AND MELTED THE STYROFOAM PACKING PEANUTS.  EACH OF THE GLASS BOTTLES WERE OF 1 QUART CAPACITY. THIS SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.  THE SHIPMENT WILL THEN BE REPACKED IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED TO ITS DESTINATION WITH CERTIFICATION PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN VERY COOPERATIVE WITH US BY PROVIDING A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (ATTACHED) AND CERTIFICATION.

CIND RAILROAD WAS IN THE PROCESS OF PICKING UP THIS CAR FROM INTERCHANGE AT NS-GEST STREET YARD, CINCINNATI, OHIO.  ON CAR INSPECTION BY FRA INSPECTOR JOE CONNELLY REVEALED SMALL LEAK IN THE DOME AREA FITTINGS.  CAR WAS MOVED TO #34 TRACK AREA AT NS YARD AND ALL CONCERNED NOTIFIED.  CAR WAS REPAIRED BY BP CHEMICAL. LIMA, OHIO.

column168: AIRCRAFT #172, FLIGHT #3003 FROM PHOENIX TO OAKLAND, APRIL 19, 1992 - HAD AN ELECTRICALLY POWERED WHEELCHAIR WHICH WAS LOADED IN THE AFT BIN. BATTERY ACID LEAKED OUT OF THE BATTERY ONTO TWO BAGS AND ON THE FLOOR. WHEN THE WHEELCHAIR WAS REMOVED, THE SPILL WAS NOTED AND THE WHEELCHAIR WAS DAMAGED.  THE SPILL WAS WIPED UP AND SENT ON TO LAS VEGAS AS FLIGHT #3010 FOR CLEAN-UP AND INSPECTION. A POLICIES AND PROCEDURES MEMORANDUM WAS SENT OUT ADDRESSING "LEAD-ACID BATTERY HANDLING" TO CORRECT THE SITUATION.  I HAVE ATTACHED THAT MEMORANDUM.

JAMES CAMPBELL, THE OPERATOR, PUT PUMP INTO WRONG DIRECTION DURING COMPARTMENT CHANGE WHILE LOADING A FIVE COMPARTMENT TANK TRAILER.  THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF A DOT VESSELL.  PRODUCT SPILLED FROM LOADING HOSE WHEN HOSE WAS DISCONNECTED FROM THE TRAILER.  (OPERATOR ERROR).
column172: Tank trailer, semi-trailer or full trailer (two axles)

column168: ON 4-16-92 AT APPROXIMATELY 01:16, SORT SUPERVISOR TOM BASLER, REPORTED A SPILL IN PRIMARY A, DIVERTOR 20, AT OUR SORT FACILITY.  HE REPORTED THE SPILL AS FOLLOWS: CLEAR LIQUID, NO ODOR, NO EMPLOYEE'S IN CONTACT. THE HAZMAT SPILL TEAM CONSISTING OF HAZMAT COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE AND P/T HAZMAT SPECIALIST NEAL VANSAUN RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL WE NOTICED ONE FIBERBOARD BOX WITH MOISTURE ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX.  THIS MOISTURE WAS PHED AND THE READING WAS 0.  THE BOX WAS OPENED AND INSIDE WE FOUND STYROFOAM PACKING MATERIAL AND NEWSPAPER AND AN INNER FIBERBOARD BOX.  WE OPENED THE INNER BOX AND FOUND IT TO CONTAINER 4-1 GAL PLASTIC BOTTLES. THESE PLASTIC BOTTLES HAD PLASTIC SCREW TYPE CLOSURES, SECURED WITH GREEN TAPE SURROUNDING THE CLOSURES. WE OBSERVED THAT THESE BOTTLES HAD MOISTURE ON THE OUTSIDE. WE PHED THIS LIQUID AND ONCE AGAIN FOUND A PH READING OF 0.  THE PH READING OF 0 INDICATES A STRONG ACID.  WE INSPECTED ALL 4 BOTTLES AND FOUND THAT 3 OF THESE BOTTLES CONTAINED COLA ACIDULANT #12364A. THESE BOTTLES WERE REPLACED IN THE INNER FIBERBOARD BOX, THE INNER BOX RESEALED, THE OUTER BOX WAS THEN RESEALED, A NOTATION OF THE AIR WAYBILL WAS MADE.  WE OBSERVED THAT THIS WAS A MULTI PIECE SHIPMENT, TOTAL OF 7 PIECES, THE BOX WAS RESEALED AND PLACED INTO A LARGE WHITE ABX PLASTIC BAG.  WE THEN CALLED CLEAR OF THE SCENE AND ADVISED HAZMAT THAT WE WOULD BE RETURNING ONCE THE REMAINING PIECES OF THE SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED.  TIME 01:33. **SEE ATTACHED REPORT**

ON 4-17-92 AT APPROX 01:33, SORT LEAK 2, JOHN PANETTA, REPORTED A SPILL AT C-47, UNLOAD B AT OUR SORT FACILITY.  HE REPORTED THE SPILL AS FOLLOWS: WHITE LIQUID, ODOR OF PAINT, NO EMPLOYEE'S IN CONTACT. THE HAZMAT SPILL TEAM CONSISTING OF HAZMAT COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE AND P/T HAZMAT SPILL SPECIALIST NEAL VANSAUN RESPONDED TO TEH SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL, WE NOTICED AN OPENED, LARGE BLUE PLASTIC BAG.  A FIBREBOARD BOX WAS SITTING ON THIS PLASTIC BAG LEAKING A THICK WHITE FLUID WHICH HAD FORMED A SMALL PUDDLE ON THE CONCRETE FLOOR.  WE DONNED ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE MASKS AND INVESTIGATED THE SOURCE OF THE SPILL. WE FOUND THE SHIPMENT TO BE "PAINT", PER THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS THAT WAS INSIDE THE INVOICE ENVELOPE THAT WAS ATTACHED TO THE BOX.  COPIES OF ALL THE PAPERWORK FOUND IN THIS INVOICE ENVELOPE WILL BE ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT. ONCE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PAPERWORK WAS FOUND, THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN PLASTIC BAGS, THE SPILL ON THE CONCRETE WAS EMULSIFIED AND CLEANED WITH SPILL PADS, THE BLUE PLASTIC BAG AND THE USED SPILL PADS WERE ALSO PLACED INTO PLASTIC BAGS FOR LATER DISPOSAL.  WE CLEARED THE SCENE AT 01:49.  WE NOTIFIED HAZMAT BASE THAT WE WOULD BE RETURNING TO BASE TO DROP OFF THIS SHIPMENT FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY A COMPROMISED FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE DURING TRANSIT. THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE CLOSURE. **SEE ATTACHED REPORT**

column168: ON 4-08-92 AT 0211 HAZMAT DISPATCH RECEIVED A CALL FROM GROUND 41, (K. BUTCHER) VIA RADIO.  THE SPILL WAS DISPATCHED AS A CLEAR LIQUID WITH AN ODOR.  THIS SPILL WAS LOCATED OUTSIDE DOOR A-15, OF A BUILDING ON THE PROPERTY OF AIRBORNE EXPRESS, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO  45177. CERT 13 (JEFFREY A. HOSTETLER) ILN HAZMAT COORDINATOR AND CERT 12, (MARK GRIFFITH) ILN PART-TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN WAS DISPATCHED VIA RADIO AND ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 0213.  UPON ARRIVING AT THE SCENE, CERT 13 AND CERT 12 DETECTED THE STRONG ODOR FROM A FIBREBOARD BOX SITTING ON TOP OF SOME FREIGHT ON A CUSHMAN.  THERE WERE THREE BROWN GLASS BOTTLES BROKEN OPEN ON THE GROUND AND A CLEAR LIQUID BESIDE THE CUSHMAN.  CERT 13 AND CERT 12 DONNED CARTRIDGE MASKS AND INVESTIGATED FURTHER.  THIS SPILL WAS CONTAINED.  THE AREA CLEANED AND THE FIBREBOARD BOX CONTAINED AND BAGGED IN FOUR PLASTIC BAGS, AND THE ODOR WAS STILL DETECTABLE.  AT 0224 CERT 07 (KAREN NICHOLS) PULLED A YELLOW "C" CONTAINER FROM THE UNLOAD TO A-14, THIS "C" CONTAINER CONTAINED TWO MORE BOXES OF THE SAME MATERIALS AND ONE WAS LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID.  CLEAR AT 0242.  THESE WERE ALSO BAGGED AND TAGGED.  THE SHIPMENTS WERE MOVED TO THE HAZ AREA FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND DRUMMED BECAUSE OF THE ODOR.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND WAS SENT THE NEXT DAY.  THE MSDA FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN 1263" AND HAD A HAZARD CLASS OF FLAMMABLE.  THESE SHIPMENTS WERE MARKED AND THE CONTENTS WERE PACKAGED IDENTICALLY. **SEE ATTACHED REPORT**
